Now I have everything I need. Let me produce the detailed implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Named-Theme System for T3 Code

This plan is structured in the order files should be written to avoid broken imports at any intermediate step. Each section covers the exact content needed along with design rationale.

---

### Step 1 — Create `packages/shared/src/theme.ts`

**Purpose:** Single source of truth for theme identity, metadata, and color tokens. This file must have zero dependencies on browser APIs or Effect, making it importable in any execution environment.

**Full content design:**

```typescript
export const BUILT_IN_THEME_IDS = ["t3-dark", "t3-light", "t3-midnight"] as const;
export type BuiltInThemeId = (typeof BUILT_IN_THEME_IDS)[number];

export interface ThemeColorTokens {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  accent: string;
  sidebar: string;
  editor: string;
  terminal: string;
  statusBar: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  id: BuiltInThemeId;
  name: string;
  isDark: boolean;
  colors: ThemeColorTokens;
}
```

**Color values to use:**

These are swatch-quality representative colors. They are the values placed in `ThemeDefinition` instances, consumed by `ThemeSelector` for rendering colored dots, and stored as CSS variables for the new `data-theme` blocks.

`t3-dark` (isDark: true):
- background: `"#0e1218"` — near-black neutral
- foreground: `"#edf1f7"` — near-white
- accent: `"oklch(0.588 0.217 264)"` — brand purple/blue
- sidebar: `"#131820"` — slightly lighter than background
- editor: `"#111519"` — slightly darker panel
- terminal: `"#0a0e13"` — deep terminal black
- statusBar: `"#1a2030"` — contrasting bottom bar

`t3-light` (isDark: false):
- background: `"#ffffff"` — white
- foreground: `"#1c2129"` — near-black text
- accent: `"oklch(0.488 0.217 264)"` — brand purple/blue (lighter variant)
- sidebar: `"#f5f6f8"` — light gray sidebar
- editor: `"#fafbfc"` — near-white editor
- terminal: `"#f0f1f3"` — light terminal
- statusBar: `"#e8eaed"` — light status bar

`t3-midnight` (isDark: true):
- background: `"#070b10"` — deeper blue-black
- foreground: `"#c8d4e8"` — slightly blue-tinted white
- accent: `"oklch(0.65 0.18 230)"` — cyan/teal accent diverging from brand purple
- sidebar: `"#0b1018"` — deep blue sidebar
- editor: `"#060a0f"` — darkest editor area
- terminal: `"#040709"` — near-pure black terminal
- statusBar: `"#0d1520"` — dark blue status bar

**Helper functions:**

```typescript
export const BUILT_IN_THEMES: ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition> = [
  { id: "t3-dark", name: "T3 Dark", isDark: true, colors: { /* values above */ } },
  { id: "t3-light", name: "T3 Light", isDark: false, colors: { /* values above */ } },
  { id: "t3-midnight", name: "T3 Midnight", isDark: true, colors: { /* values above */ } },
];

export function getThemeById(id: BuiltInThemeId): ThemeDefinition {
  const theme = BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((t) => t.id === id);
  if (!theme) throw new Error(`Unknown theme: ${id}`);
  return theme;
}

export function resolveSystemThemeId(systemDark: boolean): BuiltInThemeId {
  return systemDark ? "t3-dark" : "t3-light";
}
```

Note: `getThemeById` takes only `BuiltInThemeId` so the TypeScript type system guarantees callers cannot pass an arbitrary string, and the runtime throw guards against refactoring mistakes.

---

### Step 2 — Update `packages/shared/package.json`

Add the `"./theme"` export entry alongside the existing entries. The new entry follows the exact same pattern as `"./model"`, `"./git"`, etc.:

```json
"./theme": {
  "types": "./src/theme.ts",
  "import": "./src/theme.ts"
}
```

This file uses direct `./src/*.ts` pointing — consistent with the existing monorepo convention where Bun and `moduleResolution: "Bundler"` resolve TypeScript source directly. No compiled output step is required.

---

### Step 3 — Rewrite `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`

This is the most surgical change. The goal is to:
1. Extend the stored `AppTheme` type from `"light" | "dark" | "system"` to `BuiltInThemeId | "system"`.
2. Apply a `data-theme` attribute alongside the `.dark` class toggle.
3. Preserve the `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"` return value consumed by `DiffWorkerPoolProvider`, `DiffPanel`, `ChatView`, `ChatMarkdown`, and `ComposerPromptEditor`.
4. Add `resolvedThemeId: BuiltInThemeId` as a new output.
5. Migrate legacy stored values `"dark"` and `"light"` to `"t3-dark"` and `"t3-light"` on read.

**Complete design for the rewritten module:**

```typescript
import { useCallback, useEffect, useSyncExternalStore } from "react";
import {
  type BuiltInThemeId,
  BUILT_IN_THEME_IDS,
  getThemeById,
  resolveSystemThemeId,
} from "@t3tools/shared/theme";

export type AppTheme = BuiltInThemeId | "system";

const STORAGE_KEY = "t3code:theme";
const MEDIA_QUERY = "(prefers-color-scheme: dark)";

// Module-level state — mirrors existing pattern exactly
let listeners: Array<() => void> = [];
let lastSnapshot: { theme: AppTheme; systemDark: boolean } | null = null;

function emitChange() {
  for (const listener of listeners) listener();
}

function getSystemDark(): boolean {
  return window.matchMedia(MEDIA_QUERY).matches;
}

function migrateLegacyTheme(raw: string | null): AppTheme {
  if (raw === "dark") return "t3-dark";
  if (raw === "light") return "t3-light";
  if (raw === "system") return "system";
  if ((BUILT_IN_THEME_IDS as ReadonlyArray<string>).includes(raw ?? "")) {
    return raw as BuiltInThemeId;
  }
  return "system";
}

function getStored(): AppTheme {
  const raw = localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
  return migrateLegacyTheme(raw);
}

export function applyTheme(themeId: BuiltInThemeId, suppressTransitions = false): void {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }
  const def = getThemeById(themeId);
  document.documentElement.dataset["theme"] = themeId;
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", def.isDark);
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    // oxlint-disable-next-line no-unused-expressions
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}

function resolveThemeId(theme: AppTheme): BuiltInThemeId {
  return theme === "system" ? resolveSystemThemeId(getSystemDark()) : theme;
}

// Apply immediately on module load to prevent flash
applyTheme(resolveThemeId(getStored()));

function getSnapshot(): { theme: AppTheme; systemDark: boolean } {
  const theme = getStored();
  const systemDark = theme === "system" ? getSystemDark() : false;
  if (
    lastSnapshot &&
    lastSnapshot.theme === theme &&
    lastSnapshot.systemDark === systemDark
  ) {
    return lastSnapshot;
  }
  lastSnapshot = { theme, systemDark };
  return lastSnapshot;
}

function subscribe(listener: () => void): () => void {
  listeners.push(listener);

  const mq = window.matchMedia(MEDIA_QUERY);
  const handleChange = () => {
    if (getStored() === "system") applyTheme(resolveSystemThemeId(mq.matches), true);
    emitChange();
  };
  mq.addEventListener("change", handleChange);

  const handleStorage = (e: StorageEvent) => {
    if (e.key === STORAGE_KEY) {
      applyTheme(resolveThemeId(getStored()), true);
      emitChange();
    }
  };
  window.addEventListener("storage", handleStorage);

  return () => {
    listeners = listeners.filter((l) => l !== listener);
    mq.removeEventListener("change", handleChange);
    window.removeEventListener("storage", handleStorage);
  };
}

export function useTheme() {
  const snapshot = useSyncExternalStore(subscribe, getSnapshot);
  const { theme, systemDark } = snapshot;

  const resolvedThemeId: BuiltInThemeId =
    theme === "system" ? resolveSystemThemeId(systemDark) : theme;

  const resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark" = getThemeById(resolvedThemeId).isDark
    ? "dark"
    : "light";

  const setTheme = useCallback((next: AppTheme) => {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, next);
    applyTheme(resolveThemeId(next), true);
    emitChange();
  }, []);

  useEffect(() => {
    applyTheme(resolvedThemeId);
  }, [resolvedThemeId]);

  return { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme, resolvedThemeId } as const;
}
```

Key design decisions:
- `applyTheme` is now exported so `ThemeProvider` can call it directly without going through the hook.
- The `useEffect` now depends on `resolvedThemeId` rather than the raw stored `theme`. This correctly handles the case where the stored preference is `"system"` and the OS changes — the effect still fires because `resolvedThemeId` changed even though `theme` didn't.
- `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"` is preserved with identical semantics so all six existing call sites (`DiffWorkerPoolProvider`, `DiffPanel`, `ChatView` ×3, `ChatMarkdown`) need zero changes.
- The `migrateLegacyTheme` function runs on every `getStored()` call. It intentionally does NOT write back the migrated value to localStorage — migration only happens when the user actively opens settings and sets a new theme. This avoids surprise writes.

---

### Step 4 — Create `apps/web/src/components/ThemeProvider.tsx`

**Purpose:** Mount this once in the Wrap chain so the `subscribe` function's media query listener is active for the lifetime of the app, keeping the DOM `data-theme` and `.dark` class in sync even if no route currently renders a component that calls `useTheme()`.

```typescript
import { useTheme } from "~/hooks/useTheme";

export function ThemeProvider() {
  useTheme(); // side effect only: keeps DOM in sync via useEffect
  return null;
}
```

This is intentionally minimal. The hook already handles DOM sync. No wrapping `<div>` or `children` prop needed — TanStack Router's `Wrap` children pass-through is handled by the existing `createElement` chain.

---

### Step 5 — Modify `apps/web/src/router.ts`

The current Wrap chain is:

```
QueryClientProvider → StoreProvider → children
```

Add `ThemeProvider` as a sibling rendered inside the tree. It does not need to wrap children because it returns `null`. Place it as a sibling just before the main `children` inside `StoreProvider`:

```typescript
import { ThemeProvider } from "./components/ThemeProvider";

// Inside Wrap:
createElement(
  QueryClientProvider,
  { client: queryClient },
  createElement(
    StoreProvider,
    null,
    createElement(ThemeProvider, null),
    children,
  ),
)
```

Note: `StoreProvider`'s children prop must accept `ReactNode` (multiple children). Verify `StoreProvider`'s props signature accepts multiple children — Zustand store providers built with `createElement` using standard React children do support multiple children as rest arguments after the props object. If `StoreProvider` is typed with `children: ReactNode` (i.e., `React.PropsWithChildren`), this works as-is. If it is typed more narrowly, a `Fragment` wrapper should be used:

```typescript
createElement(
  StoreProvider,
  null,
  createElement(
    Fragment,
    null,
    createElement(ThemeProvider, null),
    children,
  ),
)
```

Check `apps/web/src/store.ts`'s `StoreProvider` type. The file shows it uses Zustand and accepts `children?: ReactNode`, so multiple children work fine.

---

### Step 6 — Add CSS variable blocks to `apps/web/src/index.css`

Append these blocks at the end of the file, after all existing content. The blocks use `data-theme` attribute selectors on `:root`. They introduce `--t3-*` prefixed custom properties to avoid any collision with the existing Tailwind `--background`, `--foreground`, etc. variables. The existing Tailwind variables remain in the `:root` / `:root @variant dark` blocks and continue to drive Tailwind utilities throughout the app — these new blocks are supplementary tokens for theme-aware surfaces that opt in explicitly.

Additionally, update the existing `:root @variant dark` block to be replaced by theme-specific blocks that also set the standard Tailwind tokens, so themes actually affect the app palette.

**Design decision on the CSS variable strategy:**

There are two complementary approaches:

**Approach A (minimal/additive):** Keep the existing `:root { ... }` and `:root @variant dark { ... }` blocks unchanged. Add `--t3-*` variables only for new theme-aware UI surfaces. The dark class still drives Tailwind dark mode. This is the safest, least disruptive path.

**Approach B (full replacement):** Replace the Tailwind variable values inside each `data-theme` block. This changes the actual Tailwind-driven palette per theme.

The requirements say "add CSS variable blocks per theme" and introduce the `--t3-background` etc. token names. This points to Approach A — the `--t3-*` variables are a separate namespace for the new theming surfaces (especially the `ThemeSelector` swatches), while the app's existing Tailwind variable topology remains stable.

The blocks to add at the bottom of `index.css`:

```css
/* Named theme token blocks — consumed by ThemeSelector swatches and
   future per-theme UI surfaces. The --t3-* namespace is separate from
   Tailwind design tokens to avoid breaking existing utility classes. */

:root[data-theme="t3-dark"] {
  --t3-background: #0e1218;
  --t3-foreground: #edf1f7;
  --t3-accent: oklch(0.588 0.217 264);
  --t3-sidebar: #131820;
  --t3-editor: #111519;
  --t3-terminal: #0a0e13;
  --t3-status-bar: #1a2030;
}

:root[data-theme="t3-light"] {
  --t3-background: #ffffff;
  --t3-foreground: #1c2129;
  --t3-accent: oklch(0.488 0.217 264);
  --t3-sidebar: #f5f6f8;
  --t3-editor: #fafbfc;
  --t3-terminal: #f0f1f3;
  --t3-status-bar: #e8eaed;
}

:root[data-theme="t3-midnight"] {
  --t3-background: #070b10;
  --t3-foreground: #c8d4e8;
  --t3-accent: oklch(0.65 0.18 230);
  --t3-sidebar: #0b1018;
  --t3-editor: #060a0f;
  --t3-terminal: #040709;
  --t3-status-bar: #0d1520;
}
```

Note: CSS custom property names use kebab-case (`--t3-status-bar`), matching CSS convention. The TypeScript `ThemeColorTokens` interface uses camelCase `statusBar`. The mapping is explicit in `ThemeSelector` which reads the JS color values from `ThemeDefinition.colors` directly, bypassing CSS variables for swatch rendering.

---

### Step 7 — Create `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`

This component replaces the inline radiogroup in the settings page. It renders the "System" option plus all three named themes.

**Structure:**

```typescript
import { BUILT_IN_THEMES, type BuiltInThemeId } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
import type { AppTheme } from "~/hooks/useTheme";
import { cn } from "~/lib/utils";

interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  value: AppTheme;
  onChange: (next: AppTheme) => void;
  resolvedThemeId: BuiltInThemeId;
}

const SYSTEM_OPTION = {
  value: "system" as const,
  label: "System",
  description: "Match your OS appearance setting.",
};

export function ThemeSelector({ value, onChange, resolvedThemeId }: ThemeSelectorProps) {
  return (
    <div role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme preference" className="space-y-2">
      {/* System option — no swatches, uses resolved theme name as detail */}
      <SystemThemeOption
        selected={value === "system"}
        resolvedThemeId={resolvedThemeId}
        onSelect={() => onChange("system")}
      />
      {/* Built-in named themes */}
      {BUILT_IN_THEMES.map((def) => (
        <NamedThemeOption
          key={def.id}
          def={def}
          selected={value === def.id}
          onSelect={() => onChange(def.id)}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**System option sub-component:**

```typescript
function SystemThemeOption({
  selected,
  resolvedThemeId,
  onSelect,
}: {
  selected: boolean;
  resolvedThemeId: BuiltInThemeId;
  onSelect: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      role="radio"
      aria-checked={selected}
      onClick={onSelect}
      className={cn(
        "flex w-full items-start justify-between rounded-lg border px-3 py-2 text-left transition-colors",
        selected
          ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8 text-foreground"
          : "border-border bg-background text-muted-foreground hover:bg-accent",
      )}
    >
      <span className="flex flex-col">
        <span className="text-sm font-medium">{SYSTEM_OPTION.label}</span>
        <span className="text-xs">{SYSTEM_OPTION.description}</span>
      </span>
      {selected ? (
        <span className="rounded bg-primary/14 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-primary">
          Selected
        </span>
      ) : null}
    </button>
  );
}
```

**Named theme option sub-component:**

```typescript
function NamedThemeOption({
  def,
  selected,
  onSelect,
}: {
  def: ThemeDefinition;
  selected: boolean;
  onSelect: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      role="radio"
      aria-checked={selected}
      onClick={onSelect}
      className={cn(
        "flex w-full items-start justify-between rounded-lg border px-3 py-2 text-left transition-colors",
        selected
          ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8 text-foreground"
          : "border-border bg-background text-muted-foreground hover:bg-accent",
      )}
    >
      <span className="flex flex-col gap-1.5">
        <span className="text-sm font-medium">{def.name}</span>
        <span className="flex items-center gap-1" aria-hidden="true">
          {/* Three color swatches: background, accent, sidebar */}
          <span
            className="size-3 rounded-full border border-black/10"
            style={{ background: def.colors.background }}
            title="Background"
          />
          <span
            className="size-3 rounded-full border border-black/10"
            style={{ background: def.colors.accent }}
            title="Accent"
          />
          <span
            className="size-3 rounded-full border border-black/10"
            style={{ background: def.colors.sidebar }}
            title="Sidebar"
          />
        </span>
      </span>
      {selected ? (
        <span className="rounded bg-primary/14 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-primary">
          Selected
        </span>
      ) : null}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Note: `ThemeDefinition` must be imported from `@t3tools/shared/theme`. The three swatches match the requirements spec: "background, accent, sidebar dots". The `border-black/10` gives swatches a subtle edge so light colors aren't invisible on white backgrounds. Swatch rendering reads from `def.colors` (JS values) rather than CSS variables — this means swatches are correct even before the browser applies the `data-theme` attribute CSS.

---

### Step 8 — Modify `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`

**Changes:**

1. Remove the `THEME_OPTIONS` const (lines 25–41 in the current file).
2. Add import for `ThemeSelector`:
   ```typescript
