### Step 6 — Add CSS variable blocks to `apps/web/src/index.css`

Append these blocks at the end of the file, after all existing content. The blocks use `data-theme` attribute selectors on `:root`. They introduce `--t3-*` prefixed custom properties to avoid any collision with the existing Tailwind `--background`, `--foreground`, etc. variables. The existing Tailwind variables remain in the `:root` / `:root @variant dark` blocks and continue to drive Tailwind utilities throughout the app — these new blocks are supplementary tokens for theme-aware surfaces that opt in explicitly.

Additionally, update the existing `:root @variant dark` block to be replaced by theme-specific blocks that also set the standard Tailwind tokens, so themes actually affect the app palette.

**Design decision on the CSS variable strategy:**

There are two complementary approaches:

**Approach A (minimal/additive):** Keep the existing `:root { ... }` and `:root @variant dark { ... }` blocks unchanged. Add `--t3-*` variables only for new theme-aware UI surfaces. The dark class still drives Tailwind dark mode. This is the safest, least disruptive path.

**Approach B (full replacement):** Replace the Tailwind variable values inside each `data-theme` block. This changes the actual Tailwind-driven palette per theme.

The requirements say "add CSS variable blocks per theme" and introduce the `--t3-background` etc. token names. This points to Approach A — the `--t3-*` variables are a separate namespace for the new theming surfaces (especially the `ThemeSelector` swatches), while the app's existing Tailwind variable topology remains stable.

The blocks to add at the bottom of `index.css`:

```css
